To create a simple search bar using PHP, we will need to use the following components:

1. **HTML** for creating the structure of the page including the form where the user can input their search query.
2. **PHP** to handle the search form submission and connect to a database if you're searching through your site's content or else where the data resides.

Here, we'll demonstrate how to create a basic search bar that looks for a term in a predefined list of items (in this example, using an array). If you want to integrate it with a database, you'd replace this with a query to fetch results from the database based on the search term.

```php
<?php

// Sample data array. In real scenario, you would use a MySQL or similar database connection.
$dataArray = [
    'Apple',
    'Banana',
    'Cherry',
    'Date',
    'Elderberry'
];

function searchItems($query) {
    global $dataArray;

    // Simple case insensitive search function
    $results = array_filter($dataArray, function($item) use ($query) {
        return stripos($item, $query) !== false;
    });

    return $results;
}

?>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        /* Basic styling to make it look better */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        #search-container {
            width: 70%;
            margin: 20px auto;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
    <div id="search-container">
        <h2>Search Here:</h2>
        <form action="" method="get">
            <input type="text" name="query" placeholder="Type to search...">
            <button type="submit">Search</button>
        </form>

        <?php
        if (isset($_GET['query']) && !empty($_GET['query'])) {
            $query = $_GET['query'];
            $results = searchItems($query);

            if (!empty($results)) { ?>
                <h3>Results for "<?php echo $query; ?>"</h3>
                <ul>
                    <?php foreach ($results as $result) : ?>
                        <li><?php echo $result; ?></li>
                    <?php endforeach; ?>
                </ul>
            <?php } else { ?>
                <p>No results found.</p>
            <?php }
        }
        ?>
    </div>

</body>
</html>
```

This example creates a search bar that looks for items in the `$dataArray` based on what the user types into the input field. The `searchItems()` function filters the array to show only those items whose names contain the searched term.

Remember, this is a very basic implementation and might not cover all your needs (for instance, it does not handle pagination or large dataset efficiently). If you need more complex features, consider integrating with a database and using more robust search functions.

